      <h2>Understanding the Chart</h2>
      <p>This birth control comparison chart includes every major contraceptive method available. Here's how to read it:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Typical Use:</strong> Effectiveness under real-world conditions, including occasional human error like missed pills or late injections.</li>
        <li><strong>Perfect Use:</strong> Effectiveness when the method is used exactly as directed, every time — the theoretical maximum.</li>
        <li><strong>Duration:</strong> How long each method lasts before it needs attention — from single-use to permanent.</li>
        <li><strong>Cost Range:</strong> Out-of-pocket estimates. Under the ACA, most insurance covers FDA-approved contraceptives at no cost.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Types of Birth Control Explained</h2>

      <h3>Hormonal Methods</h3>
      <p>Hormonal contraceptives use synthetic hormones (estrogen, progestin, or both) to prevent ovulation, thicken cervical mucus, or thin the uterine lining. These include the pill, patch, ring, shot, hormonal IUD, and implant. They tend to be highly effective but may cause side effects like mood changes, headaches, or spotting.</p>

      <h3>Barrier Methods</h3>
      <p>Barrier methods physically block sperm from reaching the egg. External and internal condoms are the only contraceptives that also protect against STIs. Diaphragms, sponges, and spermicide fall into this category but offer lower pregnancy prevention rates.</p>

      <h3>Behavioral Methods</h3>
      <p>Fertility awareness methods (FAMs) rely on tracking ovulation signs to avoid intercourse during fertile windows. Withdrawal (the pull-out method) is also behavioral. These methods are hormone-free and cost-free but depend heavily on consistent, correct use.</p>

      <h3>Permanent Methods</h3>
      <p>Vasectomy and tubal ligation/salpingectomy are surgical procedures intended to permanently prevent pregnancy. They are over 99% effective and appropriate for people certain they do not want future pregnancies.</p>

      <h3>Emergency Contraception</h3>
      <p>Emergency contraceptive pills (Plan B, ella) and the copper IUD can prevent pregnancy after unprotected sex. They are not intended as primary birth control but serve as a critical backup option.</p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>What is the most effective birth control method?</h3>
        <p>The implant and IUDs (hormonal and copper) are the most effective reversible methods, with over 99% effectiveness. Because they require no daily action, typical and perfect use rates are nearly identical. Permanent sterilization is also over 99% effective.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>What birth control options are hormone-free?</h3>
        <p>Hormone-free options include the copper IUD, external and internal condoms, diaphragms, the contraceptive sponge, spermicide, fertility awareness methods, and sterilization. These are ideal for people who experience side effects from hormonal methods or prefer to avoid synthetic hormones.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Which birth control methods protect against STIs?</h3>
        <p>Only external (male) and internal (female) condoms protect against STIs. For full protection, many healthcare providers recommend using condoms alongside a more effective contraceptive method — a strategy called dual protection.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>How do I choose the right birth control method?</h3>
        <p>Start by identifying what matters most to you: effectiveness, hormone avoidance, convenience, cost, or STI protection. Long-acting methods (IUDs, implants) offer the best effectiveness with minimal effort. If you prefer non-hormonal options, consider the copper IUD or barrier methods. Always consult a healthcare provider who can factor in your medical history.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>What is the difference between perfect use and typical use?</h3>
        <p>Perfect use assumes flawless adherence — every pill taken on time, every condom used correctly. Typical use reflects how people actually use the method, including missed doses and inconsistent use. The gap between these rates is smallest for "set and forget" methods like the implant and IUDs.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Can I switch birth control methods at any time?</h3>
        <p>Generally yes, but the process varies. Switching from one hormonal method to another usually requires overlapping methods or using backup contraception during the transition. Removing an IUD or implant restores fertility almost immediately. Always work with your healthcare provider to plan a safe switch.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>What is the most affordable birth control option?</h3>
        <p>Condoms are the cheapest option upfront. However, under the ACA, most insurance plans cover prescription contraceptives (pills, IUDs, implants, etc.) at no out-of-pocket cost. Long-acting methods may have a higher upfront cost but are the most cost-effective over time.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Does birth control affect future fertility?</h3>
        <p>Most methods do not affect long-term fertility. After stopping the pill, patch, ring, implant, or IUD, fertility typically returns within one to three menstrual cycles. The Depo-Provera shot is the notable exception — it may take 10 months or longer for fertility to fully return. Sterilization procedures are intended to be permanent.</p>
      </div>

